260
00:17:42,740 --> 00:17:47,458
Rym: So I guess we'll begin with just a description of how these two technologies work and what they are.

261
00:17:47,940 --> 00:17:51,320
Rym: We're not going to go into the deep, deep details because I doubt you care.

262
00:17:52,900 --> 00:17:54,920
Rym: So anyway, CRT, a cathode ray tube.

263
00:17:55,100 --> 00:17:57,480
Rym: Now those are the monitors that look like TVs.

264
00:17:57,700 --> 00:17:58,938
Rym: They're big and boxy and heavy.

265
00:17:59,240 --> 00:18:00,457
Scott: It's because they're essentially TVs.

266
00:18:01,282 --> 00:18:01,678
Scott: Kind of.

267
00:18:02,160 --> 00:18:11,820
Rym: Yeah, I mean basically a cathode ray tube on a very fundamental level is inside of it, it's a big funnel-shaped vacuum made of lead glass.

268
00:18:12,720 --> 00:18:13,900
Rym: And the vacuum's really powerful.

269
00:18:14,040 --> 00:18:14,820
Rym: In fact, it's dangerous.

270
00:18:15,320 --> 00:18:17,738
Rym: If you were somehow able to crack the glass, it could kill you.

271
00:18:18,660 --> 00:18:20,560
Scott: Good thing the glass is really, really, really thick.

272
00:18:20,940 --> 00:18:21,094
Rym: Yes.

273
00:18:21,520 --> 00:18:25,200
Rym: Now this isn't true in old, old, old TVs and old, old, old monitors.

274
00:18:25,620 --> 00:18:31,739
Rym: If you ever find an old, this is just a warning before I start, a really old cathode ray tube, like an old ass TV that still works.

275
00:18:32,200 --> 00:18:32,739
Scott: Stay away.

276
00:18:33,060 --> 00:18:34,678
Rym: Yeah, be very wary of it.

277
00:18:36,542 --> 00:18:41,820
Rym: But anyway, the technology, while complex, is very simple to understand.

278
00:18:42,440 --> 00:18:49,259
Rym: In the back of this funnel there's an electron gun, a cathode, and basically it shoots an electron beam at the screen.

279
00:18:50,080 --> 00:18:55,620
Rym: And on the screen are phosphors that when hit by electrons glow whatever color you want them to glow.

280
00:18:55,740 --> 00:18:57,600
Rym: Some glow blue, red, or green.

281
00:18:58,622 --> 00:19:00,640
Rym: Some can glow orange, white, but whatever.

282
00:19:00,740 --> 00:19:03,260
Rym: They use red, green, blue in modern color monitors.

283
00:19:03,748 --> 00:19:04,420
Rym: Monochrome is different.

284
00:19:04,520 --> 00:19:05,454
Rym: We don't really need to get into that.

285
00:19:07,100 --> 00:19:15,260
Rym: And basically, magnets and/or electromagnetic fields on the sides of this funnel aim this beam.

286
00:19:15,840 --> 00:19:22,878
Rym: And the beam basically goes from top to bottom, left to right, painting your pixels on the screen one by one over and over and over and over again.

287
00:19:23,480 --> 00:19:24,899
Scott: Really, really fast.

288
00:19:25,485 --> 00:19:25,548
Rym: Yes.

289
00:19:26,020 --> 00:19:26,658
Scott: Wicked fast.

290
00:19:27,181 --> 00:19:38,039
Rym: Old, old, old, old, old-ass CRTs actually mechanically scanned, but all modern ones use various magnetic bits to make it move, so there aren't really moving parts in there per se.

291
00:19:38,760 --> 00:19:45,359
Scott: That's good, because if there were moving parts they would not only suck, but be horribly slow at refreshing and such and such.

292
00:19:45,840 --> 00:19:45,933
Rym: Yep.

293
00:19:46,760 --> 00:19:50,320
Rym: Now, to talk about just modern CRTs, there are two basic types.

294
00:19:51,101 --> 00:19:53,899
Rym: And the difference used to mean a lot more than it does now.

295
00:19:54,280 --> 00:19:58,420
Rym: So you may hear fanboys talking about, "Oh, Aperture Grill is the way to go, blah blah blah,".

296
00:19:58,480 --> 00:20:00,800
Rym: but they're basically blowing smoke up your ass at this point.

297
00:20:01,822 --> 00:20:04,980
Rym: Now, there is a shadow mask and an Aperture Grill.

298
00:20:06,080 --> 00:20:11,560
Rym: And basically all this has to do with is that you have this electron beam scanning the screen and hitting phosphors.

299
00:20:12,220 --> 00:20:19,899
Rym: Now, how do you control precisely which phosphors it hits, especially when for every pixel there are three different phosphors, one of each color, red, green, blue?

300
00:20:21,082 --> 00:20:23,640
Rym: And the answer to that is either a shadow mask or an Aperture Grill.

301
00:20:24,541 --> 00:20:33,600
Rym: Now, for a long time Aperture Grills were a lot better, because basically all they are... These are the monitors that have the lines going across the sides.

302
00:20:34,720 --> 00:20:42,540
Scott: Yeah, if you look closely at your monitor, you probably don't have an Aperture Grill unless you're like a CAD professional with some CAD monitor or something.

303
00:20:43,280 --> 00:20:47,198
Scott: But the glass will actually be flat and not, you know, sort of bendy.

304
00:20:47,681 --> 00:20:49,800
Scott: But there are also shadow masks with flat glass.

305
00:20:50,040 --> 00:20:50,220
Scott: Yep.

306
00:20:50,460 --> 00:20:56,720
Scott: But Aperture Grills with flat glass, if you look really closely, not even that closely, you could see lines going across the screen.

307
00:20:57,400 --> 00:20:57,482
Rym: Yep.

308
00:20:57,665 --> 00:20:58,420
Rym: Really, really faint.

309
00:20:58,521 --> 00:21:00,017
Rym: They're much fainter now than they used to be.

310
00:21:00,560 --> 00:21:02,738
Rym: Some people find them really annoying, some people don't even see them.

311
00:21:03,480 --> 00:21:05,739
Rym: But those are called... Those basically stabilize it.

312
00:21:06,120 --> 00:21:14,280
Rym: What it is is that instead what you have is a series of vertical wires, really, really tiny wires tight together under high, high tension.

313
00:21:15,223 --> 00:21:16,519
Rym: And they go across your whole screen.

314
00:21:17,060 --> 00:21:22,600
Rym: And those two or possibly three horizontal wires hold them all in place in the proper distance apart.

315
00:21:24,001 --> 00:21:28,698
Rym: And those lines basically separate the different sets of three pixels or three phosphors.

316
00:21:29,840 --> 00:21:36,660
Rym: And because they're just vertical lines and there's nothing horizontally, the net result is that more light comes out total from the monitor.

317
00:21:37,200 --> 00:21:40,860
Rym: So Aperture Grills tended to be brighter and have higher contrast.

318
00:21:41,840 --> 00:21:46,200
Rym: Now shadow masks have caught up recently to the point that this is almost not even a consideration anymore.

319
00:21:47,020 --> 00:21:55,220
Rym: Shadow mask, which is used in most televisions and most monitors, is the same kind of idea, only instead you have a big piece of some kind of metal or plastic.

320
00:21:55,340 --> 00:21:56,040
Rym: Usually it's metal.

321
00:21:56,780 --> 00:21:57,660
Rym: Maybe it's coated in tin.

322
00:21:57,721 --> 00:21:58,439
Rym: It doesn't really matter.

323
00:21:59,042 --> 00:22:01,940
Rym: And it has a whole bunch of holes in it, usually in little triangles.

324
00:22:03,440 --> 00:22:09,839
Rym: And the electrons are basically aimed so that they go through the holes and then they hit the phosphors.

325
00:22:11,302 --> 00:22:12,780
Rym: See, that's not so difficult to understand.

326
00:22:13,700 --> 00:22:17,459
Rym: And when it comes down to it, the two technologies, it doesn't matter which one you use.

327
00:22:17,760 --> 00:22:21,360
Rym: The monitors that are made in the modern day are pretty much identical.

328
00:22:21,744 --> 00:22:22,639
Rym: It's just a matter of taste.

329
00:22:23,133 --> 00:22:23,360
Scott: Yep.

330
00:22:23,640 --> 00:22:32,839
Scott: If I were you and I was planning on buying a cathode ray tube monitor, I would buy one that is the most glass you can get for the least money you can get.

331
00:22:33,840 --> 00:22:39,939
Scott: Preferably the glass would be flat and not a curved glass, just because the flat glass is a lot nicer and easier to look at.

332
00:22:40,501 --> 00:22:42,520
Scott: And considering your computer, most things are square.

333
00:22:42,703 --> 00:22:43,559
Scott: It just, it's nice.

334
00:22:45,081 --> 00:22:52,319
Scott: And, uh, preferably takes up the least physical room, because you can get some monitors that, you know, don't, aren't a mile from the front to the back.

335
00:22:53,183 --> 00:22:57,159
Scott: You know, they're, they're, they're longer than an LCD, but there's not much you can do about that.

336
00:22:58,140 --> 00:23:01,920
Rym: Now spec wise, one of the big advantages of CRTs is that they're highly versatile.

337
00:23:02,361 --> 00:23:05,059
Rym: There's no real native resolution to a CRT.

338
00:23:05,340 --> 00:23:07,140
Rym: There's just a maximum resolution.

339
00:23:07,923 --> 00:23:10,977
Rym: And the quality will pretty much be the same, no matter what resolution you set it at.

340
00:23:11,683 --> 00:23:13,320
Rym: And you can set it to just about anything.

341
00:23:14,161 --> 00:23:23,420
Rym: This was really an advantage in the early days of LCDs, because when early LCDs came out, they generally, I mean, an LCD, as Scott will talk about, basically has one native resolution.

342
00:23:24,240 --> 00:23:26,980
Rym: Which is great, now, because the resolution is good.

343
00:23:27,380 --> 00:23:29,220
Rym: But way back in the day, it was usually kind of shitty.

344
00:23:29,660 --> 00:23:32,520
Rym: And games used all sorts of different resolutions, and it caused trouble.

345
00:23:33,340 --> 00:23:38,360
Scott: Yeah, nowadays, anything that runs full screen, you know, lets you choose your resolution.

346
00:23:38,761 --> 00:23:40,199
Scott: So, it's usually all good.

347
00:23:40,700 --> 00:23:46,280
Rym: Yeah, and if you're running one of those old DOS games on an LCD, well, I don't think you're gonna worry about the slight pixelation.

348
00:23:46,801 --> 00:23:48,199
Scott: Nah, I wouldn't worry about it either.

349
00:23:48,803 --> 00:23:51,720
Rym: But CRTs, I mean, the main benefits of them are, one, they're cheap.

350
00:23:52,360 --> 00:23:55,059
Rym: I mean, they're generally very cheap for what you get.

351
00:23:55,900 --> 00:23:59,999
