352
00:24:01,200 --> 00:24:06,660
Scott: Yeah, if you're gonna buy a CRT these days, you can find a used one at a used computer shop for, like, nothing.

353
00:24:07,481 --> 00:24:09,100
Scott: Or you can buy one on eBay for nothing.

354
00:24:09,640 --> 00:24:09,730
Scott: Yep.

355
00:24:10,001 --> 00:24:12,220
Scott: Or you can buy one from CompUSA for almost nothing.

356
00:24:12,500 --> 00:24:14,700
Rym: Now also, another advantage is that they're very durable.

357
00:24:15,382 --> 00:24:16,760
Rym: As in, the screen is glass.

358
00:24:17,246 --> 00:24:18,380
Rym: Like, glass, glass, glass.

359
00:24:18,540 --> 00:24:21,220
Rym: You couldn't break it if you tried at the front of that screen.

360
00:24:21,640 --> 00:24:29,033
Scott: Yeah, people don't seem to realize, because when you look at a TV or a CRT monitor, the picture looks like it's right behind the glass.

361
00:24:30,380 --> 00:24:34,740
Scott: If you actually get close and try to see, that glass is inches thick.

362
00:24:35,520 --> 00:24:35,838
Rym: Inches.

363
00:24:36,021 --> 00:24:43,958
Rym: If you want to see a demonstration of that, close one eye and take a finger and put it over something on your monitor, so that your finger covers it.

364
00:24:44,581 --> 00:24:50,057
Rym: Then move your head to the left or right, and you'll see the thing around your finger, because the image is actually a little ways back there.

365
00:24:51,560 --> 00:24:54,819
Rym: And the glass itself is very thick, and it's impregnated with lead.

366
00:24:55,820 --> 00:24:59,079
Rym: Now, the lead isn't there just to make the glass stronger, it's there to protect you.

367
00:24:59,160 --> 00:25:00,259
