Rym: Yeah.

381
00:25:38,720 --> 00:25:44,799
Scott: But you ever see that old Simpsons where Homer is sitting in front of the TV, and then you see the wall has, like, this black shadow around?

382
00:25:45,484 --> 00:25:47,959
Scott: You know, his body, there's, like, a silhouette of Homer on the wall?

383
00:25:48,522 --> 00:25:50,880
Scott: That was how old TVs were like then, you know?

384
00:25:50,981 --> 00:25:51,498
Scott: Not so good.

385
00:25:52,100 --> 00:25:52,170
Rym: Yep.

386
00:25:52,540 --> 00:25:58,720
Rym: Now, old CRTs, like ones made in the '80s, early, early '90s, tend to wear out for a number of reasons.

387
00:25:58,840 --> 00:26:10,839
Rym: The main reason being that there's something called outgassing that happens inside the tube, where basically ions and basically things that are heavy and aren't electrons are in the air, well, in the vacuum in there where they shouldn't be.

388
00:26:11,363 --> 00:26:16,399
Rym: And they get accelerated by the gun, and they hit the phosphor screen, slowly damaging it and wearing it out.

389
00:26:17,580 --> 00:26:22,578
Rym: Modern CRTs, that has been almost entirely mitigated by a whole bunch of cool technologies I don't have time to talk about here.

390
00:26:23,681 --> 00:26:27,000
Scott: Also, CRTs can get damaged by extra cleaning.

391
00:26:27,220 --> 00:26:35,080
Scott: Like, if you don't clean them nicely, then you'll put a bunch of little tiny scratches in the glass, which you don't notice, you know, if you clean it once, you clean it twice.

392
00:26:35,662 --> 00:26:45,718
Scott: If you clean it a hundred times over five years, eventually a million little tiny scratches in the monitor, all of which are individually invisible, will make your picture all blurry and bleh.

393
00:26:46,200 --> 00:26:49,599
Rym: However, they're still more durable screen-wise than most LCDs.

394
00:26:50,081 --> 00:26:50,399
Scott: Indeed.

395
00:26:50,600 --> 00:26:52,580
Rym: It's real easy to scratch an LCD screen.

396
